[[Category:Miskito]]

{{miskito_title|1|Nini Mary sa|My name is Mary|Pronunciation|Lesson 2}}

==''Is''==
{{miskito_model|
* Jan tara '''sa'''.
* Luis sirpi '''sa'''.
* Witin Pedro '''sa'''.
* Witin Susan '''sa'''.
* Witin tiara '''sa'''.
* Witin umpira '''sa'''
* Nini Mary '''sa'''.
* Tuktiki sirpi '''sa'''.
|
* John '''is''' big.
* Luis '''is''' small.
* He '''is''' Pedro.
* She '''is''' Susan.
* She/He '''is''' young.
* She/He '''is''' poor.
* My name '''is''' Mary.
* My child '''is''' small.
}}
{{miskito_mini_exercise|
|
# ''Make a list of the words in these sentences and try to learn their meanings.''
# ''Hide the meanings of the model sentences and try to remember what they mean.''
# ''What do the following mean?''
* Witin sirpi sa.
* Tuktiki tiara sa.
* Nini Jan sa.
* Pedro umpira sa.
|
* She/He is small.
* My child is young.
* My name is John.
* Pedro is poor.
}}

{{miskito_comment|The verb usually comes at the end of a Miskito sentence. The first verb form you will learn is '''sa''' ''is''. The subject often comes first in the sentence.}}
{{miskito_note|Notice that Miskito grammar makes no gender distinctions. Both ''she'' and ''he'' are expressed by the same Miskito pronoun, '''witin'''.}}
{{miskito_note|Notice that '''nini''' and '''tuktiki''' both mean ''my...'' (something), and both end in '''-i'''.}}

<br><br><br>

==''This'' and ''that''==
{{miskito_model|
* '''Naha''' Jan sa.
* '''Naha''' tuktiki sa.
* '''Baha''' Lucia sa.
* '''Baha''' yaptiki sa.
|
* '''This''' is John.
* '''This''' is my child.
* '''That''' is Lucia.
* '''That''' is my mother.
}}
{{miskito_mini_exercise|
What do these sentences mean?
|
* Naha sirpi sa.
* Baha nini sa.
* Naha yaptiki sa.
|
* This is small.
* That is my name.
* This is my mother.
}}

{{miskito_comment|The demonstrative pronouns are '''naha''' ''this'' and '''baha''' ''that''.}}

<br><br><br><br><br><br>

==''The''==
{{miskito_model|
* Mairin '''ba''' tiara sa.
* Waitna '''ba''' sin tiara sa.
* Buk '''ba''' tara sa.
* Buk '''na''' sirpi sa.
|
* '''The''' woman is young.
* '''The''' man is young too.
* '''The''' book is big.
* '''This''' book is small.
}}
{{miskito_mini_exercise|
What do these sentences mean?
|
* Waitna ba umpira sa.
* Mairin ba sin umpira sa.
* Mairin na yaptiki sa.
|
* The man is poor.
* The woman is poor too.
* This woman is my mother.
}}

{{miskito_comment|The general definite article ("the") is '''ba'''. The article follows the noun.}}
{{miskito_comment|There is another article '''na''' which denotes something near the speaker, and so is translated by "this".}}
{{miskito_note|Notice the parallellism between the demonstrative pronouns '''naha, baha''' and the articles '''na, ba'''!}}

<br>
==''A''==
{{miskito_model|
* Susan mairin '''kum''' sa.
* Yaptiki sin mairin '''kum''' sa.
* Aisiki waitna '''kum''' sa.
* Naha buk '''kum''' sa.
* Yul na daiwan '''kum''' sa.
|
* Susan is '''a''' woman.
* My mother is '''a''' woman too.
* My father is '''a''' man.
* This is '''a''' book.
* This dog is '''an''' animal.
}}
{{miskito_mini_exercise|
What do these sentences mean?
|
* Pedro waitna kum sa.
* Naha yul kum sa.
* Baha daiwan kum sa.
|
* Pedro is a man.
* This is a dog.
* That is an animal.
}}

{{miskito_comment|The indefinite definite article ("a" or "an") is '''kum'''. This article follows the noun too.}}
{{miskito_note|'''Kum''' is also the number "one".}}

<br><br><br>
