{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Orchideous| type=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic#Spells|Spell]]| features=Creates flowers| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Goblet of Fire/Chapter 18|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]}}
== Overview ==
'''''Orchideous''''' causes a bouquet of flowers to burst out of the end of a wand.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
This spell is used by [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Ollivander|Mr. Ollivander]] as part of the Weighing of the Wands ceremony; he uses this spell to test [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Fleur Delacour|Fleur]]'s wand.
== Analysis ==
A minor spell, this is used only to confirm, in a harmless manner, that Fleur's wand can in fact do magic to an acceptable standard.
== Questions == {{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Questions}}
== Greater Picture ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Intermediate Spoiler}}
[[Category:Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter]]

{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic| name=Avis| type=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic#Spells|Spell]]| features=Creates a flock of birds| appearance=[[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Books/Goblet of Fire/Chapter 18|Harry Potter and the Goblet of Fire]]}}
== Overview ==
The '''''Avis''''' spell causes a flock of birds to appear out of the end of the caster's wand.
== Extended Description ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Beginner Spoiler}}
This spell is used by [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Ollivander|Mr. Ollivander]] as part of the process of testing [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Viktor Krum|Krum]]'s wand in the Wand Weighing ceremony. Krum's wand is a very sturdy wand, made of hornbeam and dragon heartstring, thicker than most; the Avis spell causes it to give a report like a gun as it creates a flock of small, twittering birds that fly off through the open window.
In Harry's sixth year, [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Hermione Granger|Hermione]] performs this spell twice: once in [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Magic/Transfiguration|Transfiguration]] class, where she is the only person to be able to do it, unsurprisingly; and once a week later when she is suffering jealousy from [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Lavender Brown|Lavender]] and [[Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Characters/Ron Weasley|Ron]]'s budding romance.
== Analysis ==
This is a sixth-year spell; creation of living creatures, unlike Transfiguration from non-living objects, is not taught to Hogwarts students until quite late in their education. As such, it is a decent test of the capabilities of a wand.
== Questions == {{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Questions}}
== Greater Picture ==
{{Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter/Intermediate Spoiler}}
[[Category:Muggles' Guide to Harry Potter]]

{{miskito_title|2|Buk ba tibil ra sa|The book is on the table|Lesson 1|Lesson 3}}

==''In, on'' and ''at''==
{{miskito_model|
* John rum '''ra''' sa.
* Aisiki utla '''ra''' sa.
* Buk ba tibil '''ra''' sa.
* Yul ba tasba '''ra''' sa.
* Yaptiki windar '''ra''' sa.
* Mairin ba dur '''ra''' sa.
|
* John is '''in''' the room.
* My father is '''in''' the house.
* The book is '''on''' the table.
* The dog is '''on''' the ground.
* My mother is '''at''' the window.
* The woman is '''at''' the door.
}}
{{miskito_mini_exercise|Combine the two nouns to form a sentence, then say what it means. E.g. Mary / rum -> Mary rum ra sa. (Mary is in the room.)
|
# Pedro / utla
# tibil / rum
# yul / utla
# waitna / dur
# buk / tasba
# Lucia / windar
|
# Pedro utla ra sa. (Pedro is in the house.)
# Tibil ba rum ra sa. (The table is in the room.)
# Yul ba utla ra sa. (The dog is in the house.)
# Waitna ba dur ra sa. (The man is at the door.)
# Buk ba tasba ra sa. (The book is on the ground.)
# Lucia windar ra sa. (Lucia is at the window.)
}}

{{miskito_comment|The very common word '''ra''' is equivalent to several English prepositions, including ''in, on'' and ''at''. But it is not placed before but ''after'' the word it goes with, e.g. '''rum ra''' ''in the room''.}}
{{miskito_note|Because of its position, such a word is not called a ''pre''position but a "''post''position".}}
{{miskito_note|Sometimes people write '''ra''' attached to the preceding word, e.g. '''tibil ra''' or '''tibilra''' ''on the table''.}}

<br><br>

==Plural nouns==
{{miskito_model|
* Buk ba tibil ra sa.
* Buk '''nani''' ba tibil ra sa.
* Mairin na umpira sa.
* Mairin '''nani''' na umpira sa.
* Yul '''nani''' ba utla ra sa.
* Yul nani ba utla '''nani''' ra sa.
* Yul ba daiwan sa.
* Yul '''nani''' ba daiwan '''nani''' sa.
* Waitna na miriki sa.
* Waitna '''nani''' na miriki '''nani''' sa.
|
* The book is on the table.
* The '''books''' are on the table.
* This woman is poor.
* '''These women''' are poor.
* The '''dogs''' are in the house.
* The dogs are in the '''houses'''.
* The dog is an animal.
* '''Dogs''' are '''animals'''.
* This man is an American.
* '''These men''' are '''Americans'''.
}}
{{miskito_mini_exercise|Translate, then put '''nani''' after the word in italics and translate again.
|
# ''Tibil'' ba rum ra sa.
# Tibil nani ba ''rum'' ra sa.
# ''Tuktiki'' ba ''miriki'' sa.
|
# (The table is in the room.)<br>Tibil nani ba rum ra sa. (The tables are in the room.)
# (The tables are in the room.)<br>Tibil nani ba rum nani ra sa. (The tables are in the rooms.)
# (My child is an American.)<br>Tuktiki nani ba miriki nani sa. (My children are Americans.)
}}

{{miskito_comment|'''Nani''' placed after a noun makes it plural: '''buk''' ''book'', '''buk nani''' ''books''.}}
{{miskito_comment|Other words stay the same as in the singular, e.g. '''na''' can mean either "this" or "these" ('''mairin na''' ''this woman'', '''mairin nani na''' ''these women'') and '''sa''' means either "is" or "are" ('''Buk ba ... sa''' ''The book is...'' vs. '''Buk nani ba ... sa''' ''The books are...'').}}
<br><br>

==''We, they, these'' and ''those''==
{{miskito_model|
* '''Yawan''' tiara sa!
* '''Yawan''' rum ra sa.
* Witin umpira sa.
* '''Witin nani''' umpira sa.
* Naha ba miriki sa.
* '''Naha nani''' ba miriki sa.
|
* '''We''' are young!
* '''We are in the room.'''
* She/he is poor.
* '''They''' are poor.
* This is an American.
* '''These''' are Americans.
}}
{{miskito_mini_exercise|Translate:
|
# Witin utla ra sa.
# Witin nani rum ra sa.
# Baha nani ba tuktiki nani sa.
# Yawan miriki nani sa.
|
# She/He is in the house.
# They are in the room.
# Those are my children.
# We are Americans.
}}

{{miskito_comment|The only intrinsically plural pronoun in Miskito is '''yawan''' meaning ''we (inclusive)'', i.e. ''we'' in the sense of ''you and me'', ''we INCLUDING YOU''.}}
{{miskito_note|With '''yawan''' the verb form stays the same as for the third person, so '''Yawan ... sa''' ''We are...''.}}

{{miskito_comment|To say "they", on the other hand, we must put '''nani''' after the third person pronoun '''witin'''.}}
{{miskito_comment|Other pronouns, such as '''naha''' and '''baha''', are also pluralised by postposing '''nani'''.}}
{{miskito_note|The use of the definite article '''ba''' does not always correspond to that of "the" in English. Thus in Miskito we can say '''naha ba''' (literally "the this").}}
<br>

==''Isn't/aren't''==
{{miskito_model|
* Buk na tara '''apia sa'''.
* Nini Pedro '''apia sa'''.
* Naha John '''apia sa'''.
* Buk nani ba tibil ra '''apia sa'''.
* Tibil ba utla kum ra '''apia sa'''.
* Yawan miriki nani '''apia sa'''.
|
* This book '''is not''' big.
* My name '''is not''' Pedro.
* This '''is not''' John.
* The books '''are not''' on the table.
* The table '''is not''' in a house.
* We '''are not''' Americans.
}}
{{miskito_mini_exercise|Translate these sentences, then make them negative and translate again.
|
# ''Tibil'' ba rum ra sa.
|
# (The table is in the room.)<br>Tibil ba rum ra apia sa. (The table is not in the room.)
}}

{{miskito_comment|The negative of '''sa''' ''is, are'' is '''apia sa''' ''is not'' or ''isn't'', ''are not'' or ''aren't''.}}
<br><br><br><br>

