{{vegetable}}
[[Image:Ong choy water spinach.png|right|thumb|Ong choy water spinach]]

'''Kangkung''', also '''kangkong''', '''ong choy''', '''water spinach''', '''river spinach''', '''swamp cabbage''' is a leafy green vegetable grown throughout tropical and subtropical countries but most commonly throughout [[Cookbook:Southeast Asian cuisines|South-East Asia]].

It is usually [[Cookbook:Stir-frying|stir-fried]], but also appears in [[Cookbook:Soup|soups]] and [[Cookbook:Salad|salads]].

{{Wikipedia|Ipomoea aquatica}}

{{miskito_title|4|Yaptiki ba Miskitu aisisa|My mother speaks Miskito|Lesson 3|Lesson 5}}

==The '''-isa''' form==
{{miskito_model|
* — Yaptikam ba Miskitu '''aisisa''' ki?
* — Au. Yaptiki ba Miskitu '''aisisa'''.
* Tuktiki nani ba sin Miskitu '''aisisa'''.
* — Nanara tuktikam nani ba dia '''daukisa'''?
* — Nanara witin nani '''pulisa'''.
* — Yaptikam ba dia '''daukisa'''?
* — Witin plun '''piakisa'''.
|
* — '''Does''' your mother '''speak''' Miskito?
* — Yes. My mother '''speaks''' Miskito.
* My children '''speak''' Miskito too.
* — What '''are''' your children '''doing''' now?
* — They '''are playing''' now.
* — What '''is''' your mother '''doing'''?
* — She '''is cooking''' food.
}}
{{miskito_mini_exercise|Translate into English:
|
# Tuktiki ba utla ra pulisa.
# Mary Miskitu aisisa.
# Miguel plun piakisa.
# Mairin nani ba nanara dia daukisa?
|
# My child is playing in the house.
# Mary speaks Miskito.
# Miguel is cooking food.
# What are the women doing now?
}}

{{miskito_comment|Notice that these present tense forms all end in the letters '''-isa'''. They can each have various English translations depending on the context.}}
{| cellspacing=0 cellpadding=6 align="center"
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
ais'''isa'''
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
*''speaks''
*''is speaking''
*''speak''
*''are speaking''
|-
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
dauk'''isa'''
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
''does, makes'' (etc.)
|-
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
piak'''isa'''
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
''cooks'' (etc.)
|-
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
pul'''isa'''
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
''plays'' (etc.)
|}
{{miskito_note|You may be interested to know that the '''-sa''' at the end of these forms is actually the '''sa''' you already know ("is, are"). The remaining part of each verb is its "''i''-form", a sort of participle, which we can think of being equivalent to the English "-ing" form. According to this analysis, '''pulisa''' comes from '''puli sa''', i.e. "is/are + playing". The ''i''-form is the stem of the verb ('''dauk-, pul-''' etc.) plus the ending '''-i'''.}}
<br>

==The '''-ras''' form==
{{miskito_model|
* Aisikam ba Miskitu aisisa ki?
* — Apia. Aisiki ba Miskitu '''aisaras'''.
* Waitna ba dia plikisa?
* — Witin diara '''plikras'''.
* Tuktan na dia muni inisa?
* — Nanara witin '''inras'''.
* Tuktan nani sut pulisa.
* — Tuktikam ba dia muni '''pulras'''?
|
* Does your father speak Miskito?
* — No. My father '''does not speak''' Miskito.
* What is the man looking for?
* — He '''isn't looking for''' anything.
* Why is this child crying?
* — He '''isn't crying''' now.
* All the children are playing.
* — Why '''isn't''' your child playing?
}}
{{miskito_mini_exercise|Make these sentences negative:
|
# Tuktiki ba utla ra pulisa.
# Mary Miskitu aisisa.
# Miguel plun piakisa.
# Yaptiki buk ba plikisa.
# Mairin nani sut naha daukisa.
# Yawan (''we'') inisa.
|
# Tuktiki ba utla ra pulras.
# Mary Miskitu aisaras.
# Miguel plun piakras.
# Yaptiki buk ba plikras.
# Mairin nani sut naha daukras.
# Yawan inras.
}}

{{miskito_comment|Most verb forms cannot be negated by placing '''apia''' in front of them as with '''sa'''. To make the verb negative, remove the '''-isa''' ending and put '''-ras''' in its place.}}
<br><br>
{| cellspacing=0 cellpadding=6 align="center"
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
aisa'''ras'''
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
*''doesn't speak''
*''isn't speaking''
*''don't speak''
*''aren't speaking''
|-
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
in'''ras'''
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
''doesn't cry'' (etc.)
|-
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
plik'''ras'''
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
''doesn't look for'' (etc.)
|-
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
pul'''ras'''
| bgcolor="#ecf3f7" |
''doesn't play'' (etc.)
|}
{{miskito_note|Notice that '''ais''a''ras''' is an exception. This verb's stem is really '''aisa-''', but the '''-a-''' has dropped away in the positive form '''aisisa'''.}}
{{miskito_note|The '''-ras''' form is actually a sort of negative participle: '''aisaras, inras''' etc. mean something like "not speaking", "not crying" and so on. They can be followed by '''sa''' to make the full form '''aisaras sa''' "is not speaking" etc., but it is very common to omit '''sa''' here.}}
<br>
More notes:{{miskito_note|'''Witin diara plikras''': '''diara''' means "thing", but in negative sentences is used for "anything, nothing".}}
{{miskito_note|'''Tuktan''' is "child" when no possession is expressed (compare '''tuktika, tuktikam''' ''my/your child'').}}
{{miskito_note|'''Sut''' ''all'' follows the noun it refers to: '''tuktan nani sut''' ''all (the) children''.}}

<br><br>

